k function. \nI am running Ubuntu 14.04 with a GTX 970.\n\nThis is the output of `nvidia-smi` : \n\nMon Jul  6 20:42:28 2015  \n+------------------------------------------------------+  \n| NVIDIA-SMI 343.19     Driver Version: 343.19         |  \n|-------------------------------+----------------------+----------------------+\n| GPU  Name        Persistence-M| Bus-Id        Disp.A | Volatile Uncorr. ECC |\n| Fan  Temp  Perf  Pwr:Usage/Cap|         Memory-Usage | GPU-Util  Compute M. |\n|===============================+======================+======================|\n|   0  GeForce GTX 970     Off  | 0000:01:00.0     N/A |                  N/A |\n| 32%   33C    P8    N/A /  N/A |    272MiB /  4095MiB |     N/A      Default |\n+-------------------------------+----------------------+----------------------+\n\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n| Compute processes:                                               GPU Memory |\n|  GPU       PID  Process name                                     Usage      |\n|=============================================================================|\n|    0            Not Supported                                               |\n+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nMy key callback function works perfectly on OS X 10.10, but fails specifically on my ubuntu machine.\nI traced through the glfw code to see where the problem was and found that when I would press keys (W, A, S, D, etc.) the event handler found them to be 'chars' within the processEvent function in x11_window.c. \n\nI managed to solve my issue by checking out to glfw version 3.1.1. \n","closed_by":{"login":"elmindreda","id":133714,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEzMzcxNA==","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/133714?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/elmindreda","html_url":"https://github.com/elmindreda","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/elmindre